The Intel 8051 is an 8-bit microcontroller introduced in 1980. The Atmel AT89C51 is a low-power CMOS 8-bit microcontroller compatible with the 8051 instruction set, featuring 4KB of Flash EEPROM.

Key Features of 8051
CPU: 8-bit processor with 64KB external data/code memory space
RAM: 128 bytes internal data memory (addresses 00H–7FH)
ROM: 4KB internal program memory
I/O Ports: Four 8-bit I/O ports (P0, P1, P2, P3)
Timers: Two 16-bit timers/counters (Timer 0 & Timer 1)
Serial Port: Full-duplex UART
Interrupts: 5 interrupt sources (2 external, 2 timers, 1 serial)
Clock: Typically 11.0592 MHz crystal
Programming Environment
Keil µVision IDE: Most popular IDE for 8051 assembly and C programming
EdSim51: Free online simulator and assembler for 8051
MCU 8051 IDE: Open-source IDE with simulator
Universal Programmer: Used to burn hex file into AT89C51 chip
Memory Map
00H–1FH: Register banks 0–3 (32 bytes)
20H–2FH: Bit-addressable area (16 bytes)
30H–7FH: General purpose RAM (80 bytes)
80H–FFH: Special Function Registers (SFRs)
